{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492583","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492583"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:36:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:36:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1105"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1105","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1105"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.33,0.22,0.05,0.38,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1105"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82849"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1105","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1105"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1105"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67952"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"639"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1151"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3316"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10698"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82849"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-month history of nausea and epigastric discomfort. She has no other gastrointestinal symptoms. Her medical history includes gastro-oesophageal reflux disease, iron deficiency anaemia and osteoporosis. Her regular medications include esomeprazole, oral iron supplements, paracetamol and six-monthly denosumab subcutaneous injections. Last month she started taking celecoxib for osteoarthritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. An upper gastrointestinal endoscopy reveals a small hiatus hernia and multiple sessile polyps throughout the stomach (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications is most likely responsible for these endoscopic findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Esomeprazole","Denosumab","Oral iron supplements","Celecoxib","Paracetamol"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe endoscopic images show multiple sessile polyps scattered throughout the stomach, consistent with fundic gland polyps. These are commonly seen in patients on long-term acid suppression therapy. \u003Cstrong\u003EEsomeprazole\u003C/strong\u003E, a proton pump inhibitor, is the most likely cause as it leads to increased gastrin levels and subsequent proliferation of gastric mucosa.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDenosumab\u003C/strong\u003E is a monoclonal antibody used for osteoporosis treatment and has no known association with gastric polyp formation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral iron supplements\u003C/strong\u003E can cause gastrointestinal side effects including constipation and abdominal pain, but do not cause gastric polyps.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECelecoxib\u003C/strong\u003E, while capable of causing gastric ulceration, has only been used for one month in this patient and is not associated with polyp formation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParacetamol\u003C/strong\u003E has no known effects on gastric mucosa and does not cause polyp formation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFundic gland polyps are typically benign and may regress with cessation of proton pump inhibitor therapy. However, given this patient\u0027s ongoing reflux symptoms, the benefits of continuing acid suppression likely outweigh the risks of these benign polyps.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Long-term proton pump inhibitor use commonly causes fundic gland (hyperplastic) polyps in the stomach.","Fundic gland polyps are typically benign and may regress with cessation of proton pump inhibitors.","Upper endoscopy findings should be interpreted in the context of medication history."],"references":["Kim GH. Proton Pump Inhibitor-Related Gastric Mucosal Changes. Gut Liver. 2021; 15:646-52."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67952"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1105"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"1833"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"1833","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/1833"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/27544be0-2bcc-4988-9a79-ba8f46ff7a1e.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/27544be0-2bcc-4988-9a79-ba8f46ff7a1e.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":531,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67952","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67952"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-31T16:55:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-31T16:57:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1105"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82849"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null